  "prompt": "Is it against the law to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other crimes) appear legitimate by channeling it through a series of transactions or financial systems. This activity is considered a serious criminal offense because it helps criminals conceal the origins of their illicit funds and integrate them into the legitimate economy, which can enable further criminal activities and undermine financial systems.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Similarly, in the European Union, the United Kingdom, and other jurisdictions, strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations are in place to combat this crime.\n\nInternational efforts to combat money laundering are also coordinated through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for AML and counter-terrorism financing.",
